        <section id="aluminium-alloys">
            <h2>Aluminium Alloys</h2>
            <pre>
                Aluminium alloys in aerospace applications:
                - Account for 60%-80% of airframe weight.
                - Advantages: moderate cost, high strength, ductility, and more.
                - Disadvantages: softens above 150Â°C, stress corrosion, and galvanic corrosion.

                Aluminium alloy types:
                - Casting alloys: Used in as-cast conditions.
                - Wrought alloys: Includes non-age-hardenable and age-hardenable alloys.

                Age-hardening process:
                1. Solution treatment: Dissolve intermetallic precipitates.
                2. Quenching: Rapid cooling to produce a super-saturated solid solution.
                3. Ageing: Precipitation of strengthening phases.
            </pre>
        </section>
        <section id="manufacturing-techniques">
            <h2>Manufacturing Techniques</h2>
            <pre>
                Sheet Metal Forming:
                - Common in light aircraft.
                - Processes: Cutting, drilling, punching, folding.

                Joining Techniques:
                - Mechanical fastening: Rivets, bolts.
                - Adhesive bonding: Uniform stress distribution.
                - Surface treatment: Removes contamination, increases bond strength.
            </pre>
        </section>
        <section id="crystal-structures">
            <h2>Crystal Structures</h2>
            <pre>
                Types of Crystal Structures:
                - BCC: 48 slip planes, good strain hardening.
                - FCC: 12 slip planes, ductile.
                - HCP: 3 slip planes, limited ductility.

                Grain Boundaries:
                - Impede dislocation motion, affecting material properties.
            </pre>
        </section>
        <section id="strengthening-mechanisms">
            <h2>Strengthening Mechanisms</h2>
            <pre>
                Strengthening Techniques:
                - Strain hardening: Increases dislocation density.
                - Grain boundary strengthening: Higher grain boundary density increases strength.
                - Solid solution strengthening: Distorts lattice to resist dislocation movement.
                - Precipitation hardening: Formation of precipitates that block dislocations.
            </pre>
        </section>
        <section id="titanium-alloys">
            <h2>Titanium Alloys</h2>
            <pre>
                Applications:
                - Airframes, jet engines, landing gear.
                - Advantages: High strength, fatigue life, corrosion resistance.
                - Disadvantages: High cost, low specific stiffness.

                Phases:
                - Alpha: HCP structure, good creep resistance.
                - Beta: BCC structure, heat-treatable.
            </pre>
        </section>
        <section id="steel-alloys">
            <h2>Steel Alloys</h2>
            <pre>
                Applications:
                - Safety-critical aerospace components like landing gear.
                - Types: Mild steel, high-strength low-alloy steel, stainless steel.

                Phases:
                - Austenite: FCC structure, high temperature.
                - Ferrite: BCC structure, ductile.
                - Cementite: Hard and brittle.
            </pre>
        </section>
        <section id="phase-diagrams">
            <h2>Phase Diagrams</h2>
            <pre>
                - Binary systems: Cu-Ni (isomorphous), Cu-Ag (eutectic).
                - Terms:
                  * Liquidus: Separates liquid from solid-liquid phases.
                  * Solidus: Separates solid from solid-liquid phases.
                  * Eutectic reaction: Liquid transforms to two solid phases.
            </pre>
        </section>
